\begin_layout Section
Higher order moments about the mean
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variance is also called the second moment about the mean.
 In general, the rth moment about the mean is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu^{(r)}=E[(X-\mu)^{r}].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Proposition.
 The first moment about the mean is zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu^{(1)}=E[X-\mu]=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof.
 By linearity, 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X-\mu]=E[X]-E[\mu]=\mu-\mu=0.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NOTE.
 The third moment about the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{(3)}=E[(X-\mu)^{3}]$
\end_inset

 is related to the skewness of the distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The standard deviation of a frequency distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is the square root of the variance:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma(X)=\sqrt{\Var(X)}.
\]

\end_inset

The variance is therefore commonly represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Var(X)=\sigma^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The coefficient of variation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is the ratio of the standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CV=\frac{\sigma}{\mu}.
\]

\end_inset

We also have the percent coefficient of variation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\%CV=100\frac{\sigma}{\mu}.
\]

\end_inset

